<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / International Company News: Nissho Iwai warns of losses on
trust, share investments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nissho Iwai, Japan's sixth-largest general trading company by sales,
yesterday warned it would record extraordinary losses of Y39bn (Dollars
376.4m) during the financial year which ends today. It blamed investments in
specified money trusts, securities losses, and the costs of closing
businesses outside Japan.
The group said it planned to offset the losses through extraordinary sales
of land and securities. However, the net impact would be an extraordinary
loss of Y3bn for the 1993 financial year. Post-tax profits would fall short
of the Y7bn forecast, it warned.
Nissho Iwai is the latest of many trading houses to announce extraordinary
losses on specified money trusts. These financial instruments, known as
tokkin, were an important source of income during the late 1980s. However,
they have become a serious burden since the collapse of the Tokyo stock
market. Sumitomo, Mitsubishi and Marubeni have each liquidated unprofitable
subsidiaries and cancelled tokkin and fund trusts.
Nissho Iwai said it would report a Y16bn loss on its fund trust and tokkin
accounts. A further Y6bn loss would be incurred by scaling back similar
investments at its subsidiary NI Finance. The remaining Y17bn would be
accounted for by losses on securities and the closure of overseas
operations.
These would be partly offset by a Y5.1bn profit on land sold in Chiba, east
of Tokyo, the sale of another plot for Y24.5bn, and Y6bn from sales of
securities, it said.
</TEXT>
