<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / International Company News: Grumman offered higher price for
fast deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Northrop, which is bidding for defence group Grumman against Martin
Marietta, said yesterday it was willing to increase its offer from Dollars
60 to Dollars 62 a share if Grumman was prepared to agree an immediate
merger.
The unusual move in the Dollars 2bn battle seemed designed to exert pressure
on Grumman to change the ground rules it has laid down for an auction of the
company, which Northrop says are unfair.
However, Grumman later rejected Northrop's proposals and said it would
continue with the auction.
Grumman has called on both Northrop and Martin Marietta to submit their best
and final offers by 5.00pm New York time today. It wants to spend Easter
weekend evaluating the proposals and announce a winner on Monday morning -
laying down an unusually short timetable for a US takeover.
However, Northrop yesterday said it could not accept this timetable, arguing
that to be fair a bidding procedure must be open and public, giving each
bidder a reasonable opportunity to respond to the other's offer.
Northrop's current hostile offer of Dollars 60 a share is Dollars 5 a share
higher than the friendly bid for Grumman being made by Martin Marietta.
However, Northrop said that to demonstrate its commitment to an open bidding
process, it was prepared to proceed immediately to Dollars 62 a share, but
this would only remain on the table until 3.00pm today. If Grumman had not
accepted the offer by then, it would expire and Northrop's Dollars 60 a
share offer would remain in effect.
Northrop noted that if Grumman agreed its proposal,it would mean that the
two bidders faced the same takeover costs. At present, Martin Marietta has a
financial advantage because of a merger agreement which lays down that
Grumman will pay it Dollars 50m compensation if another bidder acquires the
company.
</TEXT>
