<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / International Company News: BASF/AlliedSignal nylon fibre
merger collapses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A plan for Germany's BASF and AlliedSignal of the US to merge parts of their
nylon fibre operations into a joint venture with annual sales of around
Dollars 1bn, has collapsed, the companies announced yesterday.
AlliedSignal said that they were unable to find a satisfactory way to
integrate their businesses but that they were well-placed in their
respective markets for textile and carpet fibre products.
The failure of talks, which were first revealed last October, is the third
recent setback to the German group's ambitious restructuring plans.
A proposed deal with Britain's ICI, under which BASF was to have exchanged
its west European acrylic facilities in return for the UK company's
polypropylene activities, failed because the German group placed too high a
value on its side of the bargain.
BASF agreed last month to pay ICI Pounds 60m (Dollars 87.6m) for its
polypropylene business, including two plants in the Netherlands and
north-east England.
Completion of this part of the deal was seen as essential at the German
company in the light of an earlier agreement between Shell and Montedison to
merge their polypropylene operations into Europe's biggest specialist
manufacturer in this sector.
Earlier last year BASF failed to sell its polyester fibre divisions to
Wellman, of New Jersey.
Fibres, which is currently combined in a single division with plastics in
BASF's operations, is one of the group's most troubled sectors. It has been
especially affected by over-capacity and price erosion in its main European
markets.
The German company said last October that the deal with AlliedSignal would
create a more cost-efficient producer with enough critical mass to compete
more effectively.
BASF officials said they had nothing to add to yesterday's announcement from
AlliedSignal, and said further explanation of the circumstances of the
break-down was unlikely.
Mr Jurgen Strube, group chairman, said earlier this month that all divisions
except plastics and fibres were making profits in the current financial
year, but forecast a return to break-even by year end.
</TEXT>
