<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Mayflower more than trebles to Pounds 5.38m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mayflower Corporation, the specialist automotive engineering group, reported
pre-tax profits more than tripled from Pounds 1.7m to Pounds 5.38m in the
year to end-December.
Operating profits from continuing operations before acquisitions rose by 58
per cent to Pounds 5.7m (Pounds 3.6m), while total operating profits
increased by 47 per cent to Pounds 5.2m.
Mayflower has grown rapidly since 1991 following the acquisition in that
year of Motor Panels and the purchase last year of International Automotive
Design (IAD).
The group is now established in both the UK and the US as an integrated
design, engineering and production operation for truck cabs and low-volume
specialist car bodies.
Group turnover jumped by 50 per cent to Pounds 102m (Pounds 67.8m). Sales
from continuing operations rose by 16.4 per cent to Pounds 74.6m (Pounds
64.1m) and Pounds 26.1m was added through acquisitions.
Earnings per share more than doubled to 2.59p, and a final dividend of 0.9p
is proposed raising the total for the year to 1.35p (1.25p).
IAD, which was acquired from the receiver, has been extensively restructured
and achieved profits of Pounds 257,000 in the eight months from April on a
turnover of Pounds 24m.
The IAD workforce worldwide has been reduced from about 1,000 to 650,
including 200 contract staff.
The lossmaking IAD subsidiary in France has been sold, while in the UK the
main IAD operation in Worthing, West Sussex, has been sold to Daewoo Motor,
the South Korean car maker.
Daewoo paid about Pounds 1m for plant and equipment from IAD, which
continues to hold project contracts with the new owner.
At home IAD has opened offices in Essex and Coventry, and has recently won
new contracts from Ford and Saab.
Group turnover and pre-tax profits are expected to continue to rise strongly
in the next couple of years as new contracts are brought into operation
including:
The supply of bodies for the Aston Martin DB7 luxury sports car to be
launched this summer;
The supply of bodies for the new MG sports car to be launched by the Rover
group in the summer of 1995;
The development and manufacture of cabs for a series of trucks for Ford in
the US, which could be worth more than Dollars 300m (Pounds 205m) over a
15-year period.
The engineering and prototype programme for the MG sports car, code-named
PR3, has been completed, and Motor Panels is currently installing the
assembly facility. It is investing Pounds 24.2m in the project.
Mayflower is forecasting annual sales of Pounds 1.5m from the Aston Martin
contract, Pounds 20m from the MG contract starting next year, and Pounds 14m
from the Ford US truck contract.
Mr John Simpson, Mayflower's chief executive, said the group had 'healthy
order books' and could expect a period of 'strong organic growth.' It
continued to look for acquisitions, he added.
</TEXT>
