<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Restructuring costs hit Grampian - Profits
fall 50% after Pounds 2.98m exceptional charge and sports loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Grampian Holdings, the Scottish mini-conglomerate, yesterday blamed heavy
restructuring costs for a 50 per cent decline in pre-tax profits to Pounds
5.63m.
The Glasgow-based pharmaceutical, sporting goods, transport and retail
group, said its results were hit by exceptional charges of Pounds 2.98m to
cover redundancies and reorganisation costs and a Pounds 398,000 operating
loss in its sporting business.
As part of the restructuring, the group has closed its pharmaceutical
factory in Glasgow, relocated the division to Leyland in Lancashire and cut
the workforce by 12 per cent to 440.
It made a further 42 workers redundant at Patrick International, its
sporting goods subsidiary which closed down operations in Germany and made
stock write-downs elsewhere.
Total closure and restructuring costs of Pounds 6.6m were offset by a Pounds
3.62m exceptional profit on the disposal of Grampian Woollen Mills, which
was merged last year with the Edinburgh Woollen Mill.
Despite the problems, Grampian said an improved performance by the transport
division, which saw profits increase 85 per cent to Pounds 2.7m, lifted
profits on continuing group operations to Pounds 11.8m (Pounds 11.3m).
The increase was also underpinned by a Pounds 1.6m profit derived from its
retained 25 per cent stake in Grampian Woollen Mills.
Mr David McGibbon, finance director, said group turnover had declined
slightly to Pounds 137.1m (Pounds 137.3m) as the pharmaceutical business
struggled to maintain sales during its restructuring.
'Some sales are bound to be lost when you're putting through a
reorganisation of this size,' he said.
The restructuring costs also forced the group to increase net borrowings
from Pounds 28.6m to Pounds 32m, representing gearing of 74 per cent
compared with 58 per cent last time.
Although exceptional items led to a 50 per cent decline in earnings per
share to 7.35p (14.71p), the previous year's figure was distorted by a
profit from the sale of Mitre, the sporting goods company.
Pre-exceptional earnings increased to 10.53p (7.18p).
An unchanged final dividend of 3.8p leaves the total payment for the year at
5.5p (same).
COMMENT
Although the restructuring of the pharmaceutical division has only just been
completed, Grampian has decided to take all the costs in 1993 in the hope
that pain now will pay off with a recovery later. There are, however,
reservations about the strength of a balance sheet which is still labouring
under heavy borrowings. Nevertheless, profits this year are expected to
bounce back to around Pounds 11m, putting the shares on a forward multiple
of 15. Although that is a discount to the market, there are some concerns
that the slimmed-down businesses can generate the necessary cash to
strengthen the balance sheet.
</TEXT>
