<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / C&amp;W and Bell Canada seek offering for joint cable group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A new cable television group linking the UK cable interests of Cable and
Wireless, Bell Canada International and Jones Intercable is planning a
public offering which could be the first to reach the London Stock Exchange.
The new cable group, to be known as BCETI Cable, which will be the third
largest in the UK, is planning a listing on the New York Stock Exchange and
probably also in London.
The groups have signed a letter of intent to consolidate their interests in
cable television and cable telephony and have announced a public offering.
C&amp;W, which has a 20 per cent stake in Bell Canada's UK cable holdings, said
last night it hoped to see a flotation in both London and New York.
Mr Alan Bates, managing director of the UK arm of Jones Intercable, a US
group, will be chief executive of BCETI Cable. He said the proposed
amalgamation meant 'our interests in the UK can achieve the full benefit of
access to both capital and expertise, allowing us to deliver a wide range of
video, voice and data products to consumers and businesses.' The group will
have significant cable interests in London, Yorkshire, East Anglia and
south-east England.
The decision to go for a flotation is a symptom of growing confidence in the
UK cable industry largely because of the dual streams of revenue from
television and telephone services.
At least three other large cable groups are considering coming to the London
Stock Exchange this year: TeleWest, Comcast and Generale Des Eaux, the
French utility and communications group.
Mr Richard Woollam, director of the Cable Television Association, said the
deal underlined the cable industry's commitment to build 'super highways' in
the UK. It could also be a chance, he said, for British investors to back
the industry. At the moment the multi-billion pound task of building cable
networks in the UK is largely being financed by North American money.
Details involving minority shareholders in the BCETI agreement are likely to
be resolved within the next couple of weeks with a prospectus likely within
two months.
</TEXT>
