<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Ferranti receivers agree to sell defence systems to GEC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Administrative receivers to Ferranti International have agreed in principle
to sell the company's main defence systems businesses to GEC rather than a
management buy-out team.
Ferranti went into receivership in December after GEC withdrew a 1p a share
offer for the company following its due diligence inquiries.
The receivers from accountants Arthur Andersen said yesterday that after
analysing the indicative bids and 'taking into account a number of important
factors' they had decided that GEC was the preferred buyer. GEC is
understood to have made a higher bid and the other factors are thought to
include its acceptability to the Ministry of Defence. The receivers and GEC
expect to conclude negotiations in April.
However, Mr Jonathon Wackett, of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, which is advising the
buy-out team said it was 'still very much in the game'. 'We are now talking
to our backers about an increased bid and other ways we could reshape our
offer.'
The buy-out team is backed by a UK institution and 'a major European defence
company', thought to be Thomson of France.
The agreement covers Ferranti Defence Systems Integration, which has around
570 employees, and Ferranti Simulation &amp; Training which has a further 540
staff.
But the buy-out team is bidding for the whole of Ferranti's systems
business, including its civil and satellite operations, which has a turnover
of Pounds 130m and 1,750 employees.
Mr Geoff Eades, a member of the buy-out team, said: 'We are trying to
preserve the greatest part of the systems business as an entity. It is a
people business and one of the dangers is that the people start walking
away.'
GEC is also thought to be negotiating with the receivers over Ferranti's US
business and its sonar joint venture with Thomson.
The receivers said separate negotiations were continuing with other
interested parties over the civil business, based in Wythenshawe near
Manchester, and the component making operation, which employs around 515 in
Oldham, Lancashire.
</TEXT>
