<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Enhanced redundancy terms for miners may be dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is likely to end British Coal's enhanced redundancy scheme
from the end of next month in a move that could encourage thousands of
miners to seek to leave the industry before then.
Replacing the scheme by a less generous package would be attacked by the
opposition and union leaders as a betrayal of the 10,000 miners still in the
industry.
British Coal hopes to soften the blow by offering a one-off bonus for miners
who go on working. In exchange it would expect miners to accept significant
changes in working practices before privatisation later this year and next.
The changes would ease problems surrounding the sell-off. They would make
British Coal more attractive to prospective bidders who, under European
legislation, will have to honour the terms and conditions governing workers
in the businesses they take over, initially at least.
Treasury restrictions make it very unlikely that British Coal could offer
both its existing enhanced redundancy package and loyalty bonuses.
Although the Department of Trade and Industry has still to make final
decisions, indications are that it would prefer the bonuses.
The likely termination of the existing redundancy package from April 30
follows a series of extensions and improvements since the scheme was
introduced in January 1990. The enhanced terms have helped British Coal
reduce its mining workforce to about a quarter of the total of more than
40,000 two years ago.
In recent closures miners have been eligible for payments of up to Pounds
44,000, and the average of about Pounds 27,000 is almost unprecedented for
manual workers in any industry.
However, with the bulk of the pre-privatisation rationalisation complete,
the political need for the scheme has diminished.
An announcement to withdraw existing terms would lead to a flood of
applications for redundancy. Although British Coal can refuse requests for
redundancy, saying no would inevitably cause morale problems.
Of the 18 remaining pits, between two and four may close before
privatisation but the closures could be effected before April 30.
British Coal may present the package as compensation for miners' failure to
win pay awards for the last two years as well as a reward for loyalty.
However, ministers are keen to change work patterns and erode demarcation
before privatisation.
British Coal declined to comment on plans for the redundancy package or
loyalty bonus. The DTI said it was a matter for British Coal.
</TEXT>
