<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Observer: The green forays
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Thai army - famous for staging 17 coups d'etat and doing well out of
logging businesses - is trying to mollify public fears of yet another
upheaval.
A senior officer has written in Thailand's Army News a piece called 'Fear no
coup'. It explains that coups are caused not by ambitious soldiers but by
the shortcomings of democracy and 'inappropriate behaviour' by politicians.
The piece adds that a typical warning sign of a coup is criticism of the
government for ineptitude by the media and academics.
Very comforting; the media have been in anti-government overdrive of late.
The Bangkok Post headlined its story on the army's views thus: 'No coup if
MPs doing good job'.
Is that over one week or three?
</TEXT>
