<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Observer: Hang loose, old boy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Phew, thank God that's over. Except it isn't. The Scott inquiry into
arms-for-Iraq - already more than a year old - still has a week's oral
testimony in May and then must be written up by Scott himself; no finer way
of ruining a summer.
Meanwhile, hacks covering the story are producing a necktie for distribution
to various Whitehall and government officials. It will feature the Roman
numeral III, representing the guideline the government allegedly breached; a
serpent, signifying Whitehall; and the motto 'distorted, wild, prejudiced',
words used by Sir Robin Butler, head of Britain's civil service, to describe
the British media's reporting of the Scott inquiry.
Since when was a tie judged a suitably satirical device? A very masculine
gadget, its choice hints rather strongly of the old-school-tie cohabitation
so often prevailing between accusing hack and accused minister. Very cosy.
</TEXT>
