<DATE>940331
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last week's episode of Murder Most Horrid, about a cunning grandmother who
outwits her scheming daughter and son-in-law every time they try to bump her
off, was the weakest so far, but this second series has been so much better
than the first that that is not saying much. In today's story Dawn French
plays travel and cookery writer Verity Hodge who moves to a little French
village to hype all things French, bullying the villagers into creating the
image she sells so successfully in her book (9.00 BBC2).
After Episode 1, BBC1's new detective series, Grushko, shot in St
Petersburg, could go either way. If the scripts sustain the interest in the
problems of Russia, and move away from the cliches and stereotypes, all
could be well. If not, this will be written off as just another crime
series, shot on exotic locations to take advantage of financial enticements
(9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
