<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Arms For Iraq - The Scott Inquiry: Cast of characters in a
Whitehall farce - In the firing line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR NICHOLAS LYELL, attorney-general, is trying to resist being set up as
the 'fall guy' if the Scott inquiry delivers a harsh verdict. However, as
the minister most directly responsible for the overall conduct of the Matrix
Churchill case, he remains vulnerable.
Sir Nicholas gave evidence which was defensive rather than convincing,
although he is widely regarded as an honest man. However, even his friends
concede that the arms-for-Iraq affair has left him politically out of his
depth.
MR WILLIAM WALDEGRAVE, minister for open government, faces opposition knives
out for him. They have been sharpening since he told the inquiry rather
lamely that he approved defence-related machine tools to Iraq because he was
not given vital intelligence about their end-use.
Mr Waldegrave, who was a Foreign Office minister from July 1988 to November
1990, has also left himself open to charges of misleading parliament. He
accepted a form of words drafted by one of his officials which did not tell
the whole truth about the government's policy towards Iraq.
Nevertheless, other evidence shows he was usually more cautious than the
more gung-ho Mr Alan Clark and Lord Trefgarne at the ministries of trade and
defence.
MR KENNETH CLARKE, the chancellor, may rue the day he promised to resign if
he was seriously criticised by the inquiry. He says he signed a PII
certificate in the Matrix Churchill case to protect the intelligence
services. But his insistence, along with the other serving minister Mr
Malcolm Rifkind, now defence secretary, and former Foreign Office minister
Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, that he had a duty to sign based on well-established
law, has since been questioned by the judge.
MR ALAN CLARK, a former trade and defence minister, has made few new friends
as a result of his involvement in the Matrix Churchill affair.
Some of his former colleagues say that it is only he who is really to blame
for the way the trial of three businessmen turned into a Whitehall farce of
potentially tragic consequences. He said one thing to Customs and Excise and
the government, and another thing to the judge.
Mr Clark's evidence to the Scott inquiry provided a further twist in the
tale when he declared that the change in the guidelines should have been
announced to parliament. He has also dropped a mischievous hint that
Baroness Thatcher, as prime minister, had known more about what was going on
that she had told the judge.
MR ALAN MOSES QC, the chief prosecutor in the Matrix Churchill trial,
performed a remarkable U-turn over PII certificates. Having argued strongly
for the application of these certificates to prevent disclosure of official
information, he told the inquiry that the system he had adhered to was
fundamentally flawed.
He also admitted to the inquiry that he may have failed in his duties as
prosecutor by not chasing some of the documents he needed.
Previously Mr Moses was regarded as on the fast track to become a High Court
judge. Some colleagues wonder if this promotion might now take a
considerably longer time.
CUSTOMS AND EXCISE: The role of Customs in investigating and prosecuting the
Matrix Churchill businessmen was not a happy one entirely.
Officials have been questioned by the judge over their failure to fully
familiarise themselves with the facts of the case, and over the way that
witness statements were drawn up.
WHITEHALL: The list of trade, defence, and Foreign Office officials who have
emerged less that sweetly from the Scott inquiry is considerable. A few are
likely to be moved sideways. Some already have been.
INTELLIGENCE SERVICES: They may escape along with the arms manufacturers,
dealers and bankers who have not been called to give evidence.
Additional reporting by David Owen and John Mason
</TEXT>
