<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Arms For Iraq - The Scott Inquiry: 'Every government gets
its knickers in a twist'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Domestic interest in the Scott inquiry has not in general been reflected
internationally. Continental European and US press coverage has been thin,
and international commentators remain puzzled by the excitement in the UK.
France
A senior executive in the defence industry:
'Every government in the world gets its knickers in the twist every once in
a while. What seems to be typically British is the apparent convergence of
businessmen, the intelligence services, and government operating a policy
which was decided at quite a high level - very John le Carre. The nearest
you come to that is in the US.
'The difference with France is that we were quite overt in our arms exports
to Iraq. The British government seems to have said one thing in public and
done another in private.'
Germany
Mr Joachim Krause, former adviser to the UN special commission on Iraq:
'The Scott inquiry has clearly pointed to the limits of export controls in
the field of dual-use goods. Whenever a government thinks it is in its
strategic interest to buttress the defence capabilities of a certain case -
even if this is a rogue state - there may be loopholes to be used or one can
simply connive with violations of existing rules.
'It has also shown that Whitehall - like Washington, Paris, Bonn, and most
Arab states - succumbed in the 1980s to Saddam Hussein's strategic
deception. Such a failure is grave and embarrassing for any government.'
United States
Mr Kenneth Juster, former senior State Department official in the Bush
administration and a partner in a Washington law firm:
'In the US everything is very open and officials are used to being
questioned in public. We have had a wide range of investigations over the
past 4 1/2 years into all sorts of Iraqgate allegations of wrongdoing . . .
hearings by several congressional committees, the turning over of every
document requested with no claim of executive privilege, including
classified information.
'So far nothing has substantiated the allegation that there was any
wrongdoing or conspiracy involving the US and the UK. What has happened is
that certain political figures have been been unjustly accused of being
criminals simply on account of policy decisions, and the energies of
government have been used up in countering false allegations. There has been
no fire but a lot of smoke.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
