<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Arms For Iraq - The Scott Inquiry: Anatomy of an inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Justice Scott will write his report during the summer with publication
expected before Christmas. He will make recommendations on Public Interest
Immunity certificates and export legislation, and although his independent
report was commissioned by the government, it is not binding in law.
There will be no public hearings in April, but some further hearings early
in May. In the meantime, the inquiry team will continue to assemble written
evidence.
So far, the inquiry has considered:
4.3m words of typescript in evidence
200,000 pages of documents, each copied five times
166 witnesses have given written evidence:
 -of these, 57 have given a total of 400 hours of oral evidence in public
 -12 have given 50 hours of oral evidence in closed session
Cost of the inquiry estimated at Pounds 940,000, mainly covered by DTI
Before making a criticism of a witness in his report, the judge will give
that witness an opportunity to make, in writing, any comment.
Every witness was sent a comprehensive request for detailed background
information as well as the questions Lord Justice Scott would ask. The
longest questionnaire, to Mr Alan Moses QC, ran to 172 pages.
Witnesses could call on lawyers, or anyone else, to assist them in preparing
written statements and to sit beside them at oral hearings.
</TEXT>
