<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Compulsory purchase fear halts Cammell Laird bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The bid by Coastline Industries to buy the Cammell Laird shipyard at
Birkenhead, Merseyside, has been put on hold after worries about whether the
site might be compulsorily purchased and government failure to provide a
Pounds 2m derelict grant.
VSEL, the Barrow nuclear submarine builder which owns the yard, had given
Coastline until today to complete the deal or withdraw.
VSEL says the deal is now off, although Coastline's advisers yesterday made
clear it has not been abandoned.
Coastline, a ship repair company, wants to buy the all-weather construction
hall, three dry docks and a wet basin. It is already leasing the facilities,
with 600 people employed. It plans to expand the workforce to 1,600 by the
end of next year.
VSEL's deadline, however, seems to have made it impossible to tie up loose
ends with Merseyside Development Corporation, a government agency with
planning authority over the site. Mr John Stafford, Coastline's chief
executive, wanted guarantees against future compulsory purchase and a Pounds
2m derelict land grant for environmental improvements. Without certainty of
these, he was not prepared to take the risk of purchase.
Compulsory purchase is an issue because Coastline was not trying to buy the
whole site - only the shipbuilding and ship repair facilities.
Mr Chris Farrow, corporation chief executive, said it was unlikely that
working shipbuilding and repair facilities would be sought for purchase.
</TEXT>
