<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / AGR N-plants lead performance table
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's advanced gas-cooled (AGR) nuclear power plants performed better
than any other atomic reactor type in the world last year.
It is a remarkable transformation for a technology which scientists
struggled for years to operate efficiently.
Last year the AGRs' annual load factor was 73.68 per cent, just ahead of
pressurised water reactors at 73.16 per cent, according to Nuclear
Engineering International, the magazine for the industry.
Only three years ago the AGRs were the world's worst-performing nuclear
plants with load factors little better than 50 per cent.
The improvement has helped Nuclear Electric, operator of five AGR plants in
England and Wales, to increase its market share to more than 25 per cent
from less than 20 per cent three years ago.
It is making a bid to become the second largest generator in those countries
after National Power.
Scottish Nuclear operates two AGR stations.
The Nuclear Engineering International survey comes before a government
review of the nuclear industry.
In the review Nuclear Electric is pressing to be privatised, and to gain
approval to build a new station at Sizewell C in Suffolk.
It is thought that the government has agreed to study privatisation
possibilities in the review, the terms of reference for which are expected
to be published the week after next at the earliest.
Nuclear Electric said yesterday that it was on course to beat its 60
terrawatt hours target for the financial year, with about 39tWh coming from
the AGRs.
The improvement in AGR efficiency has been achieved by raising power
ratings, reducing downtimes, and improving refuelling and thermal
efficiencies.
The magazine's league table showed that eight of the world's 424 commercial
nuclear reactors had 100 per cent availability during the year.
Two of them are Magnox stations owned by Nuclear Electric - Hinkley Point A
2 and Oldbury 2. Five of the top 10 reactors last year were Japanese units.
</TEXT>
