<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Channel 4 seeks review of ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Channel 4 is to seek a judicial review of a decision by the Broadcasting
Complaints Commission after complaints by two former chancellors of the
exchequer.
The commission found that Lord Howe and Lord Lawson were treated unfairly in
a Channel 4 programme on monetary policy, A Brief Economic History of Our
Times, made by Fulcrum Productions.
The commission came to its conclusion in spite of deciding that the
programme was not inaccurate in any way. It decided that the co-operation of
the two Tory peers was secured on a misleading basis.
The programme consisted, the commission found, of unrelieved criticism of
the handling of the economy by Lord Howe and Lord Lawson. Had they known the
programme makers' intentions, neither would have taken part, it said.
Channel 4 said it had considered issuing libel proceedings against
commission members, but this was considered unlikely to succeed because the
complaints body is statutory and its members are covered by qualified
privilege.
Channel 4 has been told, however, that it has a case to seek judicial review
of the decision on the grounds that the commission exceeded its powers.
It is believed that Lord Howe and Lord Lawson were given written questions
in advance by Fulcrum and also saw the extracts that were going to be used.
Lord Lawson was paid Pounds 1,000 for his interview. Lord Howe did not
receive a payment - apparently because he did not ask.
Lord Howe also complained to Fulcrum about 'negative' clips in the programme
of the main news events of the years. These included events such as the
Brighton bomb and the York Minster fire, and were used by Fulcrum to remind
people of what was going on apart from monetary policy.
Lord Howe complained in a letter to Fulcrum about the other events and
people portrayed, which included: ' . . . the Piper Alpha disaster, the
unexplained cripple in a wheelchair - even the fall of the Berlin wall is
made to look like an ugly riot.'
The 'unexplained cripple' mentioned by Lord Howe was Professor Stephen
Hawking, the physicist and author of A Brief History of Time.
</TEXT>
<XX>
