<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Row over jobless figures escalates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Angry letters between senior civil servants at the Department of Employment
and Mr John Prescott, the shadow employment secretary, were yesterday given
a public airing after he refused to apologise for making 'misleading
statements' about the official unemployment figures.
Mr Peter Stibbard, director of statistics at the department, has accused Mr
Prescott of misrepresenting the outcome of a meeting between them held
earlier this month.
He published the letters after Mr Prescott failed to retract his comments by
yesterday's deadline.
In a letter dated March 23, Mr Stibbard robustly denies a claim by Mr
Prescott that official statisticians 'now recognise that the unemployment
rate is certainly half a million more than is recorded' and had 'admitted
that changes in the way unemployment is counted have removed at least
400,000 people from the official figures'.
'I object very much to the way we have been used to shore up misleading
statements issued by Mr Prescott, particularly as we neither 'recognise' nor
'admitted' anything of the kind,' writes Mr Stibbard.
Mr Prescott, who made his comments earlier this month, yesterday stuck to
his assertion that the monthly statistics are a 'con on the public'.
'My dispute with the statistics is that they are not an accurate measure of
the level of unemployment, but that the government continues to represent
them as such,' he said.
'The monthly claimant count and quarterly Labour Force Survey both show
useful trends in the labour market. What neither show is how many people are
really out of work in the UK. That is why we need a new, broader measure to
run alongside the two,' he added.
Mr Stibbard's decision to publish the letter - a rare move for a senior
civil servant - is the latest twist in a long-standing row.
Critics of the government say the monthly claimant count, which includes
only people out of work and claiming benefit, does not capture the true
jobless total. They say it excludes nearly 1m, such as young people who are
not on Youth Training schemes but are not eligible for benefit, married
women seeking jobs and people who are on other forms of state support such
as sickness and disability benefit.
The department says its quarterly labour force survey, based on
International Labour Organisation guidelines, compensates for the
shortcomings of the claimant-count series.
</TEXT>
