<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Banks given fraud warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England has warned banks to be alert to frauds where their names
might be used to persuade investors to put money into complex schemes
offering high returns, Alison Smith and Robert Rice write.
Mr Michael Foot, head of banking supervision at the Bank, warned of 'prime
bank guarantee frauds' - schemes in which a fraudster promotes low-cost or
high-return bonds said to be issued or guaranteed by well-known banks, but
restricted to professional investors. Would-be investors must pay an advance
fee before being let in on the deal. The 'prime bank' may be unaware its
name is being used.
He emphasised that supervisors needed 'full, frank and prompt information'
from banks to enable them to focus their monitoring properly.
The Bank has also decided against any significant extension of the scope of
regulation or of the powers of regulators.
</TEXT>
