<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Binder firms see merger backing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The four largest regional partnerships within BDO Binder Hamlyn, the UK's
eighth-largest accountancy firm, have expressed tentative support for a
merger with Arthur Andersen, the fourth largest, it emerged yesterday.
Birmingham, Manchester, Newcastle and the partnership covering London and
Leeds all expressed support for the idea of a merger, proposed by Andersen
earlier this month.
These four represent more than two-thirds of Binder's total partners and
more than 70 per cent of staff and fee income, making approval for the
merger highly likely if the final terms are favourable. The remaining
partnerships are still considering the proposals, with Scotland currently
most opposed. The others are East Anglia, Northern Ireland, Bristol, Poole,
Nottingham and Wolverhampton.
Those involved in the discussions, which include topics such as partner
equity and responsibility for any litigation, are hoping to present outline
'heads of agreement' for the merger to all Binder's partners next week.
In a memo to senior partners on Monday, Mr Adrian Burn, Binder's managing
partner, said that the initial proposals would allow the firm to maintain a
separate identity within an enlarged Andersen, and continue to practise
under the Binder Hamlyn name.
He stressed that any merger would not lead to material changes in personnel,
the manner in which clients were served, or fees charged.
</TEXT>
