<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Hurd walks Euro tightrope
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservatives will campaign for the European elections on a platform
which stresses both the importance of the European parliament and the
party's commitment to national sovereignty, it emerged yesterday.
In a letter to all Conservative MPs and MEPs, Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign
secretary, urged the party to raise its sights from the debacle over
enlargement of the European Union.
Mr Hurd, the Conservative campaign manager for the election, distributed a
six-page statement of election themes, approved by Mr John Major, the prime
minister.
The document sets out to bridge the deep divisions between the party's
federalist wing, which is strongest among MEPs, and the rebellious minority
of Euro-sceptics at Westminster.
Party strategists believe the document is sufficiently broadly based to
quell murmurs of revolt from both wings that have threatened to destabilise
the Tory campaign.
However, senior ministers remain fearful that the Conservatives will perform
badly in the June 9 elections. A full-scale manifesto is expected to be
published after local government elections on May 5.
Mr Hurd told the MPs and MEPs in his letter: 'A contrast has to be made
clear between our vision of a decentralised, free-trading Europe built on
the nation states, and the centralised, interventionist, bureaucratic
superstate after which Labour and the Liberal Democrats hanker. I believe we
can unite behind an approach of this kind,' he said.
'We have the opportunity over the next few years, in particular at the
intergovernmental conference of 1996, to shape a European Union in which we
can feel comfortable. Our job now is to get that across.'
The campaign document answers complaints from MEPs that the campaign for the
last election in 1989 was too negative by acknowledging that the European
parliament has 'powers and influence'.
It accuses the parliament's socialist majority of obstructing the European
single market, and claims that Labour MEPs are committed to creating 'a
socialist superstate'.
However, the guide aims to please Euro-sceptics by drawing a clear
distinction between Westminster and the Union. It says the European
parliament 'is not a sovereign parliament like ours in Britain'.
It also emphasises Conservative opposition to the transfer of further powers
from London to the Union, and stresses British support for subsidiarity -
the principle of minimum interference in national affairs.
'The nation state is here to stay. That has been the clear message of
British Conservative governments,' the guide says. 'We don't want a Europe
which interferes in every detail of national life. Conservatives are opposed
to the creation of a federal European state.'
The document appeals to the party to 'set out the case for a more flexible,
decentralised Europe which respects national feeling and the nation state'.
</TEXT>
