<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / 'Misleading' Maxwell receiver reprimanded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A leading insolvency practitioner charged with recovering assets belonging
to Robert Maxwell was yesterday severely criticised by the Commons social
security committee for allegedly misleading MPs.
Mr Peter Phillips of Buchler Phillips, who is the receiver of the Maxwell
personal estate, over-emphasised potential recoveries in a way which allowed
his firm to 'maximise its fee income and to garner more publicity
opportunities', the committee says in a report published yesterday.
It claims that he had provided estimates of gross potential realisations
from the estate of more than Pounds 8.7m, when he knew the figure he would
be able to collect was far smaller.
The scathing report is the most critical yet issued by the committee,
chaired by Labour MP Mr Frank Field, which began examining the operation of
pension funds in July 1991 after the collapse of the Maxwell business
empire.
The report concludes that the personal estate of Mr Maxwell should now be
declared insolvent and a trustee in bankruptcy appointed. It urges that this
job should not be given to Mr Phillips.
Mr Phillips yesterday said he was 'outraged' at the report. 'I can only view
this as a publicity-seeking exercise from a committee which sadly, after
months of investigation, has produced nothing of any impact,' he said in a
statement. 'Mr Field has continually and deliberately ignored the facts I
have presented to him. With hindsight I now regret the enormous amount of
time I have spent helping the committee.'
The report says that Mr Phillips and his lawyers, Nabarro Nathanson, have
charged more in fees - at Pounds 1.1m - than the total value of the Maxwell
assets that he will be able to recover.
It says that his firm's and his lawyers' average hourly fees - at Pounds 167
and Pounds 193 respectively - are the highest rates among the four sets of
Maxwell insolvency practitioners, and highlights that he charged a higher
proportion of his work at partner rates than the other firms.
Mr Phillips said the work he was carrying out needed more experienced
staffing, and stressed that he had recovered assets totalling more than
Pounds 5.3m, much of which had then been claimed by other parties.
Members of the committee were irritated by early discussions they held with
Mr Phillips at which they believe they were misled over the amount of money
that he would be able to realise.
Mr Neil Cooper, of accountants Robson Rhodes, liquidator of the
Maxwell-controlled fund manager Bishopsgate Investment Management, said:
'There remain a number of questions to be answered on Maxwell to do with
banking, regulation, the duties of auditors and the like. I think they are
much more important than this sort of thing.'
</TEXT>
