<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / PIA urged to register agents individually
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Personal Investment Authority, the new watchdog to protect private
investors, should register every adviser and sales agent individually, one
of the regulators it is replacing said yesterday.
Sir Kenneth Clucas, chairman of Fimbra, the self-regulating organisation for
independent financial advisers, told the cross-party Treasury committee of
MPs that Fimbra was 'disappointed' that the PIA had been deterred from
opting for individual registration because the number of sales agents
employed by life companies was so great.
Fimbra registers IFAs individually, but the numbers in that sector of the
financial services industry are significantly smaller. Both a system of
individual registration and a publicly available register of those who have
been subject to disciplinary action have been among the ideas backed most by
MPs in the inquiry into financial regulation.
Sir Kenneth, who originally proposed a single regulator for retail financial
services, also suggested that the Securities and Investments Board, the
City's chief regulator, should be made more accountable.
He proposed that it should be answerable to the Audit Commission, the
government's spending watchdog.
In the Commons MPs raised some fundamental doubts about the regulatory
system - in particular about the way it had operated over the sale of
personal pensions to people transferring or opting out of occupational
schemes.
Addressing what he admitted was an area of concern, Mr Peter Lilley, social
security secretary, said the government would soon issue guidance for
employers on how they could advise their employees about pensions -
including personal pensions - without infringing the Financial Services Act.
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, accused the government of
having allowed 'unacceptable practices' to develop in the selling of
personal pensions.
Mr Alistair Darling, Labour spokesman on City affairs, forecast that the
establishment of the PIA would prove to be a 'stop-gap solution'.
Replying to the debate, Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to the
Treasury, described the PIA as the 'best show in town' and said he believed
it was 'on track'. He insisted: 'The PIA should not be deflected by the
self-interest of some of its detractors.'
A Labour motion condemning the government's failure to prevent widespread
abuse in the sale of personal pensions and advocating direct regulation of
the pensions and financial services industry was defeated by 55 votes
(309-254).
</TEXT>
