<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Channel 4 challenges ruling on complaints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Channel 4 is to seek a judicial review of a decision by the Broadcasting
Complaints Commission after complaints by two former chancellors.
The commission found that Lord Howe and Lord Lawson were treated unfairly in
a Channel 4 programme on monetary policy, A Brief Economic History of Our
Times, made by Fulcrum Productions.
The commission came to its conclusion in spite of deciding that the
programme was not inaccurate in any way. It decided that the co-operation of
the two Tory peers was secured on a misleading basis.
The programme consisted, the commission found, of unrelieved criticism of
the handling of the economy by Lord Howe and Lord Lawson. Had they known the
programme makers' intentions, neither would have taken part, it said.
Channel 4 has been told it has a case for judicial review on the grounds
that the commission exceeded its powers.
Lord Howe also complained to Fulcrum about 'negative' clips in the programme
of the main news events of the years.
He said these included: ' . . . the Piper Alpha disaster, the unexplained
cripple in a wheelchair - even the fall of the Berlin wall is made to look
like an ugly riot'.
The 'unexplained cripple' was Professor Stephen Hawking, the physicist and
author of A Brief History of Time.
