<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Cardoso quits as finance minister
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso yesterday resigned as Brazil's finance
minister, as expected, in order to run in October's presidential elections.
His replacement is Mr Rubens Ricupero, a former ambassador in Washington,
who is due to take up his new post soon after Easter.
Mr Cardoso said his departure would not endanger the anti-inflation package
he has negotiated through Congress. 'If there was a risk the plan would be
altered, I wouldn't consider leaving,' he said. 'The programme's complete,
there's nothing left to do.'
Mr Ricupero says he fully supports the plan and will keep Mr Cardoso's team
of advisers.
The biggest doubt about the implementation of the final stage of the plan, a
new currency, stems from President Itamar Franco. Although he allowed Mr
Cardoso to run economic policy, even where it contradicted the president's
populist instincts, it is not clear whether Mr Ricupero will have the same
freedom.
Inflation is not likely to fall until a new currency is introduced later
this year. According to some indicators, inflation has increased sharply in
recent weeks to over 40 per cent a month. If prices continue to rise, there
is a risk Mr Franco will demand urgent, unorthodox action.
Today is the last effective day for candidates to resign from office before
the constitutionally imposed deadline. Mr Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva of the
left wing Workers' Party leads the opinion polls. Other main candidates are
Mr Orestes Quercia, who has the backing of the Brazilian Democratic
Movement, the country's largest political party.
Mr Paulo Maluf, right-wing mayor of Sao Paulo, surprised analysts by
announcing he would not run. He is thought to have been dissuaded because
the Liberal Front party, his natuaral ally, appears keener on an alliance
with Mr Cardoso.
</TEXT>
