<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / EU boosts duty-free allowance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European travellers will from tomorrow be allowed to bring almost four-times
more goods into the European Union from other non-EU countries such as
Turkey or the US, the European Commission said yesterday. The new allowance
raises the monetary limit on goods purchased at duty-free shops outside the
union from Ecu45 (Pounds 34) to Ecu175. The decision had been taken as part
of a general reform of the European customs system, which is seeking to give
European consumers greater freedom to bring in tax-free goods for personal
consumption. The allowance for duty-free goods bought within the union has
been doubled to Ecu90, although the numerical quotas for cigarettes and
alcohol brought into the union from non-EU countries will remain the same.
