<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / IRA puts pressure on London with ceasefire plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL and TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Provisional IRA last night announced an unconditional, 72-hour
ceasefire, starting at midnight next Tuesday, in an effort to force
clarification of the Downing Street peace declaration.
The move - announced as Mr John Major, the prime minister, flew to Northern
Ireland for a short visit - is being seen as an attempt to expose any
differences in strategy between the British and Irish governments. It is
also intended to renew pressure on them to open a fresh dialogue with the
republican movement.
A statement issued last night in Dublin said that the IRA hoped the
ceasefire would be accepted 'in the spirit in which it is offered' and
called on the British government to take advantage of the new development.
But Mr Major dismissed as 'cynical' the decision to call a ceasefire,
describing it as a 'public relations gesture'. In a speech in Belfast, he
told the IRA that they were mistaken if they thought the move would alter
the situation. 'Temporary ceasefires are welcome for the peace of mind they
bring for a period,' he said. 'But unless they become permanent and
irrevocable, they will not end the conflict.'
But Mr Albert Reynolds, the Irish prime minister, appeared more
conciliatory. He described the IRA move as 'a very small step in the right
direction. I am encouraged on the one hand but disappointed on the other,
because while it is a small step it is only for a short period.
'What everybody wants to see are clear signs and signals that we are on the
road to developing a permanent peace process.'
Mr Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein president, said the ceasefire represented an
important initiative and a chance to break the stalemate. He urged Mr Major
to take the opportunity to open immediate, direct talks with Sinn Fein.
Mr John Hume, leader of the mainly Catholic Social Democratic and Labour
party, declined to say whether he thought the British government should now
hold talks with Sinn Fein but said 'no stone should be left unturned' in
seeking an end to violence. He said that, if the IRA leadership were
bluffing, they would 'be isolated in a way they've never been isolated
before'.
The ceasefire comes a few days after London and Dublin moved quickly to
close an apparent split in attitudes over the likely response to a temporary
ceasefire. Comments by Mr Dick Spring, Irish foreign minister, had suggested
that Dublin might look more positively than London on a short-term halt to
violence.
Ulster Unionists were quick to condemn the IRA announcement. Mr Ken
Maginnis, their security spokesman, said he believed the ceasefire was
intended to portray Mr Major as 'intransigent and responsible for a
carefully pre-planned return to violence'.
</TEXT>
