<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Wall Street stocks slide amid fears of interest rates rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US share prices plunged again yesterday as investors sold stocks amid
growing fears about rising long-term interest rates and the outlook for a
rapidly-weakening US equity market. It was the fourth big decline on Wall
Street in the last five days.
In Tokyo, stocks opened lower amid concern about the sharp retreat in US
share prices. The Nikkei 225 index fell about 50 points to 19,510 in early
trading.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed down 72.27 at 3,626.75, its lowest
level since November 4, 1993. The Dow has fallen almost 250 points, or 6 per
cent, since last Thursday.
Traders said the selling was not triggered by any particular news, but
blamed the declines on growing fears among investors that long-term interest
rates, which have climbed sharply since February, will rise steadily
throughout the rest of the year.
Yesterday, the yield on the benchmark 30-year government bond - the chief
measure of long-term interest rates - rose to 7.1 per cent, its highest
level in 13 months.
Analysts say interest rates have been rising because bond market investors
are worried that recent rapid growth in the US economy will push up
inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income assets like bonds. Bearish
comments about the outlook for share prices from Ms Elaine Garzarelli, the
influential equities analyst at Lehman Brothers, served to further darken
the stock market's mood.
Ms Garzarelli, whose pronouncements have been closely followed since she
predicted the stock market crash in 1987, said the indicators she uses to
forecast the market had fallen sharply in recent months.
The Lehman analyst said: 'We feel the odds are about 50-50 that we may
already be in the 10 per cent to 15 per cent correctional phase.'
She had originally forecast a decline of no more than 10 per cent.
London share prices were hit by Wall Street yesterday. The Dow's overnight
fall knocked 36 points off the FT-SE 100 at the opening. The index later
recovered all but 5.7 points, but then slid to 3,092.4, a net loss of 31.
Floating-rate gilts auction a success, Page 35
World stocks, Page 43
London stocks, Page 46
</TEXT>
