<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 94 / Senior ministers rally to defend embattled Major: Tory
backbenchers warn PM that a leadership challenge is likely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, ROLAND RUDD and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior cabinet ministers yesterday sought to shore up Mr John Major's hold
on Downing Street as backbench support for his leadership haemorrhaged
rapidly in the wake of the debacle over enlargement of the European Union.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, and
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, all issued strong public
declarations of support for the prime minister.
Mr Hurd definitely ruled himself out as a candidate for the leadership. The
foreign secretary, who stood against Mr Major in 1990, said: 'I don't regret
having had a go but I am not going to have another.'
However, Mr Clarke startled some MPs by saying that he intended to succeed
Mr Major as leader of the Tory party when the prime minister stepped down.
He told BBC Radio 4's PM programme: 'I intend to succeed John Major when
John Major of his own volition goes, which I think will be a long way away.'
Mr Clarke's comments were seen by some MPs as an attempt to stall the strong
stream of support that has been developing behind Mr Heseltine.
But his declaration that the prime minister would remain in office did
little to cool the feverish atmosphere at Westminster, where centre and
leftwing Tory MPs joined rightwingers in condemning Mr Major's handling of
the enlargement negotiations.
Few were prepared to call publicly for his resignation. But most said a
leadership challenge in the autumn was inevitable unless the Conservatives
performed unexpectedly well in the local, European and Commons elections due
in the next three months.
'Both wings of the party are agreed that John Major will have to go after
the June elections,' one leading leftwing Tory MP said.
It emerged that informal talks have taken place between the Lollards, the
main backbench grouping on the left of the party, and the rightwing '92
Group.
Downing Street officials said Mr Major's mood was 'robust', and insisted
that he was not depressed by the almost uniformly hostile media reaction to
the enlargement deal.
In a speech to businessmen in Belfast last night, Mr Major again defended
his handling of negotiations over European Union voting, saying he was 'a
realist seeking to secure our success'.
He also hardened his challenge to the European Commission to ensure that the
safeguards agreed on majority voting should be maintained. 'If this deal is
not upheld, no one should expect the UK to continue the normal process of
Community business,' he said.
In Westminster, the prime minister's best hope appeared to be that tempers
on the back benches would cool during the 10-day Easter parliamentary
recess, which begins today.
A senior cabinet minister said privately, however, that the outlook for Mr
Major was bleak unless the mood of MPs had changed dramatically when they
returned from constituencies.
The mood of crisis was deepened by the disclosure that two of the four
rightwing cabinet ministers who opposed the enlargement deal - Mr Michael
Howard, home secretary, and Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the
treasury - had breakfasted at Mr Portillo's London home.
Mr Portillo's friends said the pre-arranged breakfast had no connection with
the leadership fever. However, it stoked speculation that cabinet
rightwingers were plotting.
Mr Peter Lilley, the rightwing social security secretary, further fuelled
the impression of cabinet manoeuvring in a strongly Thatcherite speech
praising the 'intellectual tide of the 1980s'.
Mr Lilley, giving the first Spectator lecture in London, said Conservative
ideas could dominate the 1990s if they were expressed with 'vigour and
conviction' - qualities widely associated in the party with Baroness
Thatcher.
In a phrase which drew attention to the prime minister's deep unpopularity
in the opinion polls, Mr Lilley ended by urging the Conservatives to take
Sir Winston Churchill's advice and 'trust the people'.
Meanwhile, Mr Heseltine said Mr Major would lead the Conservatives into the
next election and 'win it with a large majority'. However, when asked to
rule out contesting a leadership contest, he sidestepped the question.
How the British blundered in Brussels, Page 2
Panic and rumours, Page 8
In peril on stormy seas, Page 20
</TEXT>
