<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / International Captial Markets: SocGen's derivatives boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Societe Generale is preparing to launch a derivative product - known as
Boosts - aimed at investors who expect a period of stability in a particular
market, writes Tracy Corrigan.
Boosts is an acronym for 'Banking on overall stability'. It is designed for
long-term institutional investors, particularly those whose funds are
limited to certain markets, who seek to enhance their returns during periods
of stagnation.
The purchaser of a Boost anticipates that a certain instrument, such as a
government bond, will trade within a certain band for a specific period of
time. Every day the underlying instrument remains in the band, the purchaser
earns Dollars 1 (if the underlying instrument is denominated in dollars).
Thus if a one-year Boost remains in this range throughout its life, the
investor earns Dollars 365 (less the upfront cost of the product). Existing
strategies such as 'straddles', 'strangles' and 'butterflies', all using
options, express a similar view on the market.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Societe Generale.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6221 Commodity Contracts Brokers, Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
