<PROFILE>_AN-EC3DVAG0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940330
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / International Company News: La Rinascente seeks to increase
capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN SIMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
La Rinascente, Italy's largest retailing group, plans a substantial capital
increase.
The move has prompted speculation in Milan that La Rinascente, which is
controlled by the Agnelli family's Ifil holding company, is planning to put
in a bid for the Gs supermarkets and Autogrill restaurants, which are being
sold as part of the government's privatisation of the remains of its SME
foods group.
La Rinascente is to raies a total of L48.7bn (Dollars 29.8m) in new capital
through the issue of ordinary shares. The company also plans a L390bn
debenture loan to be co-ordinated by Mediobanca.
La Rinascente, together with the Centromarca foods consortium and FinComit,
the finance arm of Banca Commerciale Italiana, has expressed interest in the
SME concerns.
La Rinascente said group stores increased sales by 10.7 per cent, to
L5,579.4bn, in 1993. Net profits were up from L102.2bn to L105.3bn. It is
lifting its dividend from L190 to L200.
Belleli, the Mantua-based engineering group with a strong presence in the
Middle East, increased group sales to L1,380bn in 1993, compared with
L1,295bn the previous year.
Snia Fibre, the fibres arm of the Fiat group, has won shareholder approval
for a L152.5bn capital increase to tackle heavy restructuring costs. Snia
Fibre incurred a net loss of L49.6bn in 1993, against a loss of L66bn in
1992.
</TEXT>
